<DOCNO> AP900612-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when eskimo whaling crews on the arctic 
ocean want to determine the weather they scan the sky study the 
ice test the wind and observe the currents then they might turn 
on the radio for the whaling forecast 
the national weather service this spring bought a vhf radio 
transmitter to broadcast forecasts at least three times daily for 
whalers out on the ice near barrow 
its additional safety its made quite a difference said 
eugene brower president of the barrow whaling captains 
association the old and the new work together its just more 
refined 
until this spring the weather service had sent its whaling 
forecasts on citizens band radio which whalers complained 
frequently was interrupted or fuzzy vhf signals usually used for 
shipping and aviation offer much better reception and range 
the whaling captains met last year with the services barrow 
station manager chuck evans and offered to buy a vhf transmitter 
for direct communications with crews on the ice 
the weather service liked the idea enough that it decided to pay 
for the radio evans said the radio can transmit as far as 50 
miles from barrow 
floating ice strong currents high winds and fog are the main 
dangers to whalers 
if the wind blows the ice wrong it could trap the boats and 
crush them evans said if we see anything thats unusual or 
could be a hazard to them then we broadcast more frequently 
the whalers keep the radios at their camps on the ice brower 
said and find the extended forecasts predicting weather for the 
next few days most helpful 
its insurance they havent been wrong he said before 
we used to have some doubts but this spring theyve been right on 
the money rain snow how strong the wind is ice conditions 
eskimo whalers still use ancient forecasting methods as well he 
said things that we have observed over time 
some of the oldtimers would look at the sun the moon and let 
us know whats happening said brower weve never learned the 
full knowledge they had 
the eskimo spring whaling season usually starts in midapril and 
runs through may as the whales head for their summer feeding 
grounds 
the fall season begins in august when the bowheads migrate 
south past the arctic slope and through the bering strait 
although commercial whaling is banned eskimos are allowed to 
hunt a limited number of whales for their own use the 
international whaling commission sets annual quotas this years 
quota for the seven eskimo spring whaling villages is 44 bowhead 
whales 12 of those for barrow 
more than half that total has been reached 
no eskimos have died while whaling in recent years brower said 
but some crews lost their camps and equipment in 1988 when the ice 
broke up 
we have a lot of respect for the moving ice out there he 
said 
eventually the weather service hopes whalers will give 
forecasters a better grasp of arctic weather evans said 
they listen to what weve got compare it with what they know 
and they go with it said evans 
we can tell them all kinds of information and thats not going 
to change their minds its the knowledge they have of the ice that 
matters 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

