<TEXT>
texas a major center for oil drilling 
refining and transportation isnt ready for the mammoth spill in 
the gulf of mexico that could come from a supertanker burning 
offshore a state official said monday 
this is our worst nightmare said land commissioner garry 
mauro who serves on the governors oil spill advisory committee 
were not ready to deal with a catastrophic oil spill off the 
coast 
but gov bill clements disagreed saying texas is hoping and 
praying that the worst doesnt happen but if it does well be 
ready 
because of the potential for a major oil spill state 
government has been put on alert the state is taking each and 
every precaution possible clements said protecting our 
environment is paramount 
by midday the tanker mega borg had spilled up to 100000 
gallons of its 38 milliongallon cargo of light crude oil the 
coast guard estimated the nearly 886footlong ships aft remained 
above water but waves occasionally washed over it slightly 
increasing the chance it could sink the coast guard said 
the norwegian ship has been on fire since an explosion saturday 
while it transferred cargo 57 miles southeast of galveston 
the response to the disaster was delayed during the weekend as 
firefighting and oil containment equipment was brought in from 
louisiana alabama and even the netherlands coast guard officials 
said 
at a news conference monday coast guard adm williams merlin 
said private salvage and containment companies responding to the 
fire had equipment stationed elsewhere because there are more 
offshore fires in the north sea and the middle east than in the 
gulf 
little of the specialized equipment exists in the world and the 
coast guard does not determine where it is assigned merlin said 
the coast guard supervises cleanups but they usually are funded by 
ship owners who hire private contractors to do the work 
this is free enterprise at work merlin said the salvage 
companies that operate in this area find more business overseas 
than they do here 
we would love to have all that equipment immediately 
available he said 
the coast guard is satisfied that the mega borgs owner 
mosvolds shipping of farsund norway is acting responsibly and 
professionally merlin said 
texas ports handle 300 million tons of cargo each year 75 
percent of it crude oil or petroleum products according to mauro 
the commissioner criticized the state for failing to have a plan 
for dealing with disasters like the mega borg fire 
there is no plan to deal with 38 million gallons of oil on the 
water he said anything that happens to deal with this crisis 
is going to be a makedo emergency plan and the chances of a major 
catastrophe occurring are much higher as a result of no plan 
however other state officials said the response has gone well 
so far 
time and good weather have been on our side said state 
emergency management coordinator robert lansford 
texas water commission chairman buck wynne said the state can 
better respond to shippng disasters thanks to a recent drill that 
simulated a 200000gallon oil spill in the gulf 
hopefully weve identified problems in coordinating a 
response to a major oil spill said wynne whose agency is part 
of a regional response team that includes the coast guard and other 
federal agencies 
i think we are as ready as we can be he said 
mauro said texas deals well with small spills but is not ready 
for a large one 
he recommends that the state consolidate oil spill emergency 
planning in one agency instead of the current five buy and deploy 
cleanup equipment along the gulf coast and get more federal 
equipment placed in texas 
clements said putting more equipment along the texas coast has 
been debated 
its terribly expensive equipment and a lot of people are 
involved he said you never seem to have the people and 
equipment where the problem arises 
</TEXT>
