<TEXT>
a supreme court decision to overturn a flag 
protection law is a political gift to republican conservatives who 
have seen some of their best themes blunted by events beyond their 
reach 
president bush waved the flag with great skill in the last 
election although the top issues for republicans in the 1980s were 
taxes and defense 
but the upheaval in central and eastern europe has taken the 
steam out of the advocates of continuing the us military buildup 
then bush opened the door to a tax increase as part of his 
budget summit with congress blurring partisan lines 
in addition the supreme courts ruling last year expanding 
states power over abortion has proven electorally difficult for 
many in the gop 
if the court had upheld the antiflagburning statute congress 
approved last year that issue too would have been pushed into the 
political background 
but monday the court cooperated in a way that will force the 
democraticcontrolled congress to decide straightup on a 
constitutional amendment to ban flag burning democrats had dodged 
an amendment last fall by passing the law protecting the flag only 
to see that political cover taken from them with this 54 ruling 
congressional republicans want to stand up and salute 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan wasted no time defining 
the upcoming vote as a test of patriotism 
i happened to be at arlington cemetery on memorial day and 
some stranger asked me why dont they bring the flag burners out 
here to see the graves he said 
ill place my money on the young men and young women who serve 
in americas armed services the rest can place their money with 
the flag burners he said 
there are those of us whove fought for that flag and regard 
it as a precious national symbol said house minority leader 
robert michel rill 
for democrats opposed to the amendment the issue is undoubtedly 
a loser they were left arguing monday that the issue shouldnt be 
made partisan and taken alone isnt enough to defeat any of their 
candidates this fall 
house and senate democratic leaders seem ready to bring the 
matter up quickly which could help minimize the political impact 
and give supporters less time to whip up passions anew 
democrats their own ranks divided on the issue attacked 
republicans for trying to take advantage 
to drag the flag through cheap politics is every bit as 
offensive as burning it said democratic national chairman ron 
brown 
but republicans made clear they were in no mood to give 
democrats a free ride 
i think its a good valuedefining issue said ed rollins 
cochairman of the house gops campaign committee if your 
opponent is for flag burning then hes got to go through a very 
sophisticated explanation of why he is 
wendy democker spokeswoman for the republican senatorial 
campaign committee rattled off her select list of democratic 
incumbents who voted against the constitutional amendment last 
year when it was rejected 
she included sens max baucus dmont claiborne pell dri 
tom harkin diowa paul simon dill and carl levin dmich 
all of whom now have strong republican challengers in this years 
elections 
howard schloss spokesman for the democratic congressional 
campaign committee said the issue wont work because every 
member is for protecting the flag honoring the flag there is no 
member of the house of representatives who is saying lets burn 
the flag 
what this means is theyre desperate for anything that comes 
along schloss said if this is the only issue for them 
theyre in trouble 
schloss said democrats who vote against the constitutional 
amendment would successfully defend their positions and then move 
on to important issues such as education the environment and the 
economy 
but the democrats wont be able to keep the lid on the political 
rhetoric 
bush who used the news media and flag issue effectively in his 
1988 campaign is already planning to beat the drum as he campaigns 
around the country for gop house and senate candidates republicans 
hope it will help them in their quest to upset enough democrats to 
take control of the senate for the first time since 1980 
when the issue was hot last year democrats said they returned 
to their home districts and found voters were less concerned about 
the flag issue than other things 
but that was when it appeared a simple statute the one thrown 
out monday might suffice 
it also wasnt an election year when a complex legal issue can 
be boiled down to usorthem simplicity as dole said monday it 
would make a good 30second spot 
 
</TEXT>
