<DOCNO> AP900612-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are excerpts from the supreme courts 54 
decision monday that overturned the federal law banning flag 
burning 
the opinion of the court was written by justice william j 
brennan justice john paul stevens wrote the dissent 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
from the majority opinion 
the governments interest in protecting the physical 
integrity of a privately owned flag rests upon a perceived need 
to preserve the flags status as a symbol of our nation and certain 
national ideals but the mere destruction or disfigurement of a 
particular physical manifestation of the symbol without more does 
not diminish or otherwise affect the symbol itself in any way 
the governments interest cannot justify its infringement on 
first amendment rights we decline the governments invitation to 
reassess this conclusion in light of congress recent recognition 
of a purported national consensus favoring a prohibition on 
flagburning even assuming such a consensus exists any 
suggestion that the governments interest in suppressing speech 
becomes more weighty as popular opposition to that speech grows is 
foreign to the first amendment 
government may create national symbols promote them and 
encourage their respectful treatment but the flag protection act 
goes well beyond this by criminally proscribing expressive conduct 
because of its likely communicative impact 
we are aware that desecration of the flag is deeply offensive to 
many but the same might be said for example of virulent ethnic 
and religious epithets vulgar repudiations of the draft and 
scurrilous caricatures punishing desecration of the flag 
dilutes the very freedom that makes this emblem so revered and 
worth revering 
 
from the dissent 
the flag uniquely symbolizes the ideas of liberty equality and 
tolerance ideas that americans have passionately defended and 
debated throughout our history the flag embodies the spirit of our 
national commitment to those ideals 
the flag is a reminder both that the struggle for liberty 
and equality is unceasing and that our obligation of tolerance and 
respect for all of our fellow citizens encompasses those who 
disagree with us indeed even those whose ideas are disagreeable 
or offensive 
thus the government may indeed it should protect the 
symbolic value of the flag without regard to the specific content 
of the flag burners speech 
the prohibition does not entail any interference with the 
speakers freedom to express his or her ideas by other means it 
may well be true that other means of expression may be less 
effective in drawing attention to those ideas but that is not 
itself a sufficient reason for immunizing flag burning 
the freedom of expression protected by the first amendment 
embraces not only the freedom to communicate particular ideas but 
also the right to communicate them effectively that right 
however is not absolute the communicative value of a wellplaced 
bomb in the capitol does not entitle it to the protection of the 
first amendment 
the integrity of the symbol has been compromised by those 
leaders who seem to advocate compulsory worship of the flag even by 
individuals whom it offends or who seem to manipulate the symbol 
of national purpose into a pretext for partisan disputes about 
meaner ends 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900612-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is a chronology of events involving the 
supreme courts decisions on flagburning and efforts to reinstate 
penalties for desecration 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
june 21 the supreme court in a 54 ruling declares that 
burning the american flag as a form of political protest is 
constitutionally protected free speech saying we do not 
consecrate the flag by punishing its desecration the defendant 
in the case gregory johnson had burned the flag at the 1984 
republican convention in dallas 
 
june 22 sen pete wilson rcalif introduces a proposed 
constitutional amendment to protect the dignity of the us 
flag a flagburning is reported in berkeley calif president 
bush tells a new york audience flag burning is wrong dead 
wrong 
 
june 23 the senate passes legislation to outlaw flag 
desecration the sponsor sen joseph biden ddel says he is 
confident the measure is constitutional house speaker thomas 
foley dwash says changing the constitution should be viewed 
with caution 
 
june 26 president bushs spokesman says bush supports 
legislation to restore criminal penalties for flag desecration but 
hadnt decided whether to back a constitutional amendment to 
overturn the supreme court decision 
 
june 27 bush calls for a constitutional amendment to bypass 
the supreme court ruling saying i will uphold our precious 
right to dissent but burning the flag goes too far the house 
approves a resolution expressing profound concern over the 
court decision 
 
june 29 bush and congressional republicans agree on a proposed 
constitutional amendment house members hold an allnight 
speechmaking session on the flag issue in an empty chamber 
 
july 13 congress opens hearings on the flagburning issue 
with conservatives seeking a constitutional amendment but democrats 
backing a change in law instead 
 
july 27 the house judiciary committee approves a 
flagprotection bill over republican objections that it wouldnt 
overcome the supreme court decision 
 
aug 10 the american bar associations policymaking body 
votes to oppose a constitutional amendment to ban flag desecration 
 
sept 12 the house votes 38038 to approve legislation 
restoring criminal penalties for flagburning 
 
sept 21 the senate judiciary committee approves a proposed 
flag bill and disapproves a constitutional amendment but sends both 
to the floor for action 
 
oct 15 the senate approves a flag desecration bill 919 bush 
says he respects the intention but still will seek a 
constitutional amendment 
 
oct 12 the house votes final approval for the flag bill 
37143 the next day bush says hell allow the bill to become law 
without his signature 
 
oct 19 the senate defeats an antiflagburning constitutional 
amendment with the 5148 vote falling 16 votes short of the 
twothirds majority needed for passage 
 
oct 28 the flag desecration law takes effect and minutes 
later a seattle crowd torches a pile of american flags chanting 
burn baby burn four people were arrested flag burnings 
occur in other cities in following days and three people were 
charged with burning a flag on the us capitol steps on oct 30 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
feb 21 a federal judge in seattle rules the flag desecration 
law is unconstitutional 
 
march 5 a federal judge in washington dc rules the law is 
unconstitutional the law provides for direct appeal to the supreme 
court 
 
may 14 the supreme court hears arguments on the new flag 
desecration law 
 
june 11 the supreme court in a 54 split identical to that in 
the 1989 ruling strikes down the new federal law that outlaws 
burning the american flag it says the ban dilutes the very 
freedom that makes this emblem so revered 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

