gov bob martinez signed oilspill 
prevention and cleanup legislation he called the nations most 
comprehensive as a supertanker fire off texas highlighted the 
threat to coastal states 
this legislation puts florida in a much better position to 
deal with an oil spill and even to prevent one from happening in 
the first place martinez said monday 
the law a compromise with oil shippers and retailers was 
prompted by last years exxon valdez spill in alaska 
martinez noted that firefighters were battling to keep a burning 
norwegian supertanker with 38 million gallons of oil from sinking 
in the gulf of mexico off galveston texas 
these are real problems that do occur martinez said to 
our knowledge theres not another state in the union that has a 
bill of this comprehensive nature dealing with oil spills 
i believe that others will begin to follow suit he said 
they have coastlines to protect and the only way to protect is 
to be able to immediately respond 
highlights of the law 
vessels and terminals must produce detailed spillresponse 
plans and terminals must buy equipment to contain a spill quickly 
only certified pilots or deputy pilots may move large ships in 
florida waters 
where oil and other pollutants are loaded and unloaded in large 
quantities terminal operators will have to use booms to seal off 
the waters around the ship in case a spill occurs 
liability limits for spill damage and cleanup costs for 
transporters and owners of cargo jump from 14 million to 50 
million 
fines of up to 25000 can be assessed if shippers or terminals 
fail to meet the laws provisions 
in addition if oil drilling is approved off floridas coast 
the cap on a state spillcleanup fund will double from 50 million 
to 100 million using an existing 2centabarrel excise tax on oil 
and other pollutants 
if the fund which now contains 32 million is depleted by a 
major spill the tax could be increased to 10 cents by the governor 
and cabinet 
environmentalists generally praised the law as a positive first 
step but said more must be done 
in particular the limits on cleanup liability for oil companies 
and shippers should be removed said ann whitfield of the florida 
public interest research group she noted the 2 billion cost of 
the exxon valdez spill 
this is a dramatic improvement but it still maintains the 
principle that the oil industry should be protected from cleanup 
costs she said 
if they were not protected it would be a financial incentive 
for them to have the safety equipment to do the job 
