<TEXT>
three rounds of bargaining have produced 
little progress in resolving a contentious trade dispute with japan 
over sales of amorphous metals us officials report 
following a day of discussions monday a us trade official 
said the japanese are refusing to comply with us demands to 
remove barriers to sale of the product invented by allied signal 
inc of morristown nj 
the trade official who briefed reporters on condition of 
anonymity said the talks have gotten only about 10 percent of the 
way toward a settlement he said another round of bargaining would 
be held in midsummer 
the official said the japanese are contending they need more 
time to test the product for which allied signal won the patent in 
1973 amorphous metals marketed under the name metglas are used 
in electric transformers to cut energy transmission losses 
they want to spend the next two to three years testing the 
official said we are saying if they wanted to they could get 
this thing moving a lot faster 
the dispute is considered a major test case of the bush 
administrations efforts to break down japanese trade barriers 
because it involves a hightechnology product with a potential for 
40 million to 50 million in annual sales in japan 
allied signal contends it has been unfairly blocked from selling 
its invention in japan for more than a decade because the japanese 
want to foster development of a rival amorphous metals product to 
be sold when the allied signal patent runs out in 1993 
last april us trade representative carla hills postponed 
taking any action on the allied signal petition for economic 
sanctions against japan saying she would first seek a negotiated 
settlement of the dispute she set a sept 15 deadline for reaching 
such a settlement 
allied signal sold 18000 electric transformers using amorphous 
metals in the united states last year and projects us sales will 
reach 50000 new units this year 
