the agreement will put an end to the hardships suffered by the 
people of nepal as a result of a major interruption in the flow of 
essential consumer goods said the independent indian express 
newspaper 
relations between the two neighbors soured in march 1989 when 
rajiv gandhi then indias prime minister closed 13 of the 15 
goods transit points on its border with nepal when trade and 
transit treaties expired 
gandhi imposed the restrictions after nepal refused to agree to 
indian demands for a single treaty covering both trade and transit 
india refused to renew the existing treaties 
india saw nepals refusal to negotiate a single treaty as 
reflecting a desire to forge economic ties with other countries at 
indias expense 
india also was apparently concerned about nepals increasingly 
close ties with its northern neighbor china in 1988 india 
opposed a decision by nepal to purchase a large quantity of 
antiaircraft weapons from china 
the border closings severely restricted the flow of imports to 
nepal which have to be transported overland from indian ports to 
the himalayan kingdom nepals exports are not significant 
during the past 15 months new governments took over in both 
countries and moved to resolve the disputes 
singhs national front coalition replaced gandhis government in 
december bhattarai was sworn in as head of an interim coalition 
government in april after an eightweek prodemocracy campaign 
forced king birendra to end a partyless system of government 
the new agreement basically restores the situation as it existed 
before march 1989 when the treaties expired the two countries have 
agreed to begin negotiations on new trade and transit treaties but 
did not set any date 
