districts in northeastern sri lanka witnesses said more than 85 
people were killed 
the clashes were the worst since a ceasefire was declared in 
sri lanka 13 months ago between the rebels and the government of 
president ranasinghe premadasa the new truce was to take effect 
wednesday 
government officials speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
agreement had been reached in negotiations by justice minister 
shahul hameed and tamil tiger in jaffna a tiger stronghold in 
northern sri lanka 
a tiger spokesman contacted by telephone in jaffna and also 
speaking on condition of anonymity confirmed the agreement 
tamil rebels a minority in sri lanka are fighting for more 
political autonomy they claim they are discriminated against by 
the majority sinhalese 
tamils make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
while sinhalese comprise 75 percent 
journalists and residents contacted by telephone in batticaloa 
on tuesday said the dead in fighting that began sunday included 30 
tamil civilians in the villages of chavalakadai and chadayantalawa 
batticaloa residents said the city was deserted and that 
transportation was halted and shops businesses and schools were 
shut down they reported heavy fire by helicopter gunships 
the tigers took virtual control of the northeastern districts 
after indian peacekeeping forces withdrew in march premadasas 
government which has been negotiating with the tigers for the past 
year requested the indians departure 
at least 11000 people including 1200 indian soldiers have 
been killed in the tamil war since it started in 1983 another 
6000 people have been killed since 1987 in a backlash to tamil 
demands whipped up by sinhalese guerrillas 
</TEXT>
