<TEXT>
algerians cast ballots today in the 
countrys first contested elections since french rule ended in 
1962 but some opposition parties contended the voting was rigged 
and urged a boycott 
the main challenge to the national liberation front which has 
held sole power since this north african country gained its 
independence was expected to come from the fundamentalist islamic 
salvation front 
police were deployed throughout the country but there were no 
reports of violence 
authorities said the heavy police presence was to protect 
voters but they also feared violent street protests if the 
fundamentalists failed to win a majority 
other opposition parties looked for a low turnout among the 
countrys 13 million eligible voters as an indication of support 
for their boycott call 
they claimed the election was rigged in favor of the national 
liberation front because the ruling party controls nearly all the 
media has greater resources than other parties to help get out the 
vote and has its functionaries in the local government offices 
where the votes will be counted 
in all 11 parties were contesting the election which is to 
fill nearly 15000 seats on 1541 municipal councils and 48 
provincial councils 
elections for the national peoples assembly or parliament are 
not scheduled until 1993 but president chadli bendjedid could 
decide to advance the date for parliamentary elections depending on 
the outcome of the municipal voting 
until recently the national liberation front was the countrys 
only legal political party its candidates continue to enjoy access 
to state funds office space and the media although there have 
been official efforts to assist the new parties 
the national liberation front is an oldline marxist party born 
out of the algerian independence struggle it has abandoned its 
efforts to turn algeria into a oneparty socialist state although 
the front takes note of islam as a major tradition in algeria it 
has steered clear of fundamentalism 
the islamic salvation front the best organized among the new 
parties wants to establish the islamic legal code the sharia as 
law and openly opposes the democratic process 
we expect the people to give us 75 percent of the vote said 
islamic salvation front leader ali madani a philosophy teacher 
hundreds of university faculty members wrote a letter to 
algerian newspapers denouncing madanis remarks as a provocation 
some of the countrys most important opposition political groups 
were either barred from the elections or calling for a nationwide 
boycott the opposition covers a broad political spectrum 
including communists social democrats and conservatives 
the algerian popular party the national liberation fronts main 
rival during the independence struggle against france was among 
several parties refused official recognition by the government and 
barred from fielding candidates 
two other opposition parties the front of socialist forces and 
the movement for democracy in algeria chose not to run and instead 
called for an election boycott 
the movement for democracy is a leftist populist group headed by 
former president ahmed ben bella who was forced out of office by a 
military coup n 1965 and now lives in exile in switzerland 
the front of socialist forces is headed by berber leader ait 
ahmed a historic figure in the countrys liberation struggle it 
is a middleoftheroad group that places strong emphasis on 
preserving the berber language 
many algerian women have little say in the elections under the 
countrys islamic family code any man can vote on behalf of his 
wife or wives without producing a document authorizing him to do 
so 
the attitude of the 120000strong algerian military could prove 
decisive for the countrys political future 
the fundamentalists have called for the military to intervene to 
establish an islamic republic but senior army officers seem more 
likely to support a state free of religious interference 
</TEXT>
