dispute over the future of germany 
gorbachev suggested in a speech today to the supreme soviet 
legislature that he could accept a german associative 
participation in nato provided that there were no changes in the 
mutual obligations that east germany now has to the east bloc 
and west germany to nato gorbachev also said the two military 
alliances both must be transformed from their cold war status 
bush fielding a question from reporters indicated that the 
gorbachev proposal was not new but had come up during the 
superpower summit here two weeks ago 
our position is well known to him which is that a unified 
germany should be in nato with no conditions said the president 
who was observing his 66th birthday today but the more talking 
we do the more convinced i am that they will see that what were 
proposing is more stabilizing and is best for the soviet union as 
well as western europe and eastern europe 
so well keep on trying bush added but these ideas let 
them float them out there and well listen and well discuss them 
without rancor 
bush met monday with east germanys first noncommunist leader 
prime minister lothar de maiziere who said afterwards that nato 
must be significantly changed if soviet concerns about 
membership for a united germany are to be met 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the united states 
believes considerable progress has been made in persuading 
gorbachev that a unified germany inside the western alliance will 
not threaten soviet security or european peace 
i made clear to him what psychological difficulties this would 
signify de maiziere said after his oval office meeting with 
bush i made clear to him that it must be a significantly changed 
nato in order to be acceptable to our east european neighbors 
de maiziere said he and bush agreed that creating a new lasting 
and stable security order in europe is possible only if the role 
of the soviet union is written into it 
the prime minister added that membership in the north atlantic 
treaty organization for a united germany is only thinkable if a 
treaty clearly defines the status of soviet troops now stationed in 
east germany 
it remains open whether such a treaty should be between nato and 
the warsaw pact or between germany and the soviet union he said 
de maiziere said bush insisted that questions over such a treaty 
would have to be resolved by the countries negotiating the 
unification of east and west germany 
a white house statement said bush and de maiziere agreed that a 
united germany should enjoy full sovereignty from the time of its 
unification with no discriminatory constraints on its sovereignty 
and that germany should be free to choose its own alliance 
arrangements 
the march election of de maiziere chairman of the east german 
christian democratic union replaced a once rigidly communist 
regime he now heads a government rapidly moving to unify with west 
germany he was responsible for church affairs in the government of 
hans modrow the last communist leader 
fitzwater said bush stressed his belief that a united germanys 
membership in nato is essential for european security and will pose 
no threat to the soviet union 
