<TEXT>
two environmental groups said today they had 
filed a federal lawsuit in south carolina to try to block the 
restart of a federal nuclear weapons plant closed more than two 
years ago for safety reasons 
the suit by the natural resources defense council and the energy 
research foundation was filed monday in us district court in 
columbia said daniel w reicher an attorney for nrdc 
the energy department which owns the savannah river site has 
said it intends to restart the first of savannah rivers three 
active reactors by next january the plant produces tritium gas for 
nuclear warheads 
the reactors were closed in 1988 after an accident at one 
facility raised troubling questions about safety standards and the 
risk of mechanical failures more than 1 billion is being spent to 
upgrade the reactors and retrain workers 
energy secretary james d watkins has said the timetable for 
restarting the plant is tentative but that putting the reactors 
back in production soon is vital to the nations security 
tritium decays at a rate of 55 percent a year so the 
quantities in warheads must be replenished the government says its 
stockpile of tritium is running low although information about 
tritium inventories is classified 
a secretary in the energy departments public affairs office 
said no one was immediately available to comment on the lawsuit 
reicher said the suit contends that the government should not be 
permitted to restart the k reactor at savannah river until it 
completes construction of a cooling tower for water discharged from 
the reactor into manmade lakes environmental groups contend the 
water at temperatures of up to 180 degrees interferes with fish 
migration and causes other environmental damage 
the cooling tower is scheduled for completion in 1992 
reicher said the department could remain in compliance with the 
federal water pollution control act of 1972 without finishing the 
cooling tower if president bush issued a waiver of the pollution 
requirements on national security grounds 
bush has given no indication of whether he would grant such a 
waiver 
the weapons plant whose reactors were built in the early 1950s 
is situated on a 315squaremile federal reservation near aiken 
sc along the savannah river 
</TEXT>
