gorbachev recounted his discussions at the washington summit 
with president bush on a united germany joining the north atlantic 
treat organization the western military alliance east germany is 
a member of the sovietled warsaw pact 
our position is thus we could agree to the joining if you 
accept associative participation the principle of blocs coming 
together in conjunction with the unification of germany in the 
process of which mutual obligations are not changed neither from 
the side of west or east germany and if simultaneously the blocs 
are reformed in natural connection with vienna and the alleuropean 
process 
gorbachev did not define his concept of associate membership for 
germany vienna is the site of talks on arms cuts and the 
europewide conference on security and cooperation aimed at 
reducing tensions 
bush asked by reporters in washington about gorbachevs speech 
today said a unified germany should be in nato with no 
conditions 
but bush said he stands ready to listen and discuss without 
rancor any ideas the soviets have for solving the dispute over 
the future of germany 
official radio moscow explained gorbachevs comments saying 
it might be possible to agree with germany being in nato as an 
associated member provided there are changes in the nature of the 
military alliances both nato and the warsaw treaty organization 
gorbachev appeared to be demanding that a united germany fulfill 
east germanys obligations to the warsaw pact only during a 
transition period when the function of the two military blocs 
would change 
a western diplomat speaking on condition of anonymity said 
gorbachevs comments appeared to signal positive movement on 
the german question but he said it was still unlikely gorbachevs 
position would be acceptable to the western allies without further 
modification 
previously the soviet union sought membership in both nato and 
the warsaw pact for a united germany 
a west german newspaper reported monday that at a meeting in 
