environments and failing to give adequate handling instructions 
to customers the citations were based on 1988 inspections by the 
federal agency 
mark fenner a 3m spokesman said the company will study the 
charges and respond within the allotted 30 days the manufacturer 
also has 30 days to pay or protest the fine 
we are surprised by the size of the proposed penalty fenner 
said 
the nrc ordered 3m in february 1988 to recall all 52000 of its 
air ionizers air guns that are used to change the electrical 
charges of atomic particles during manufacturing the ionizers are 
filled with polonium a radioactive substance 
by changing electrical charges the devices are able to 
eliminate static and dust in computer chips chemicals or in the 
air 
between 1500 and 2000 of the 3m ionizers were used by 
companies that make food beverages pharmaceuticals and cosmetics 
the nrc said monday it was unlikely that any consumer products were 
contaminated or that any handlers of the devices were exposed to 
significant radiation 
the agency said its inspection identified seven violations of 
its policies 
according to the nrc summary of the inspection 3m sales 
representatives willfully failed in some cases to perform 
evaluations to assure that customers would use static eliminators 
only in acceptable environments which would not cause leakage 
strasma said some sales were made to customers required to test 
for radiation leaks but not equipped to make the tests 
