the senate ethics committee today opened two 
weeks of triallike hearings into the financial dealings of sen 
dave durenberger warning the minnesota republican that he could 
face strong sanctions 
the panel said earlier it found substantial credible 
evidence that the 12year senator broke senate rules and federal 
law in transactions involving his minneapolis condominium a book 
promotion deal and free limousine rides 
committee chairman sen howell heflin dala told durenberger 
today the committee had to answer two questions whether he 
violated senate rules or laws and whether his conduct had 
discredited the senate 
looking straight at durenberger heflin a former chief justice 
of the alabama supreme court said if the evidence clearly and 
convincingly leads me to the conclusion that you have violated the 
public trust i will not hesitate to recommend appropriate 
sanctions 
in opening its first hearings in nine years on charges that a 
senator abused his office committee members also promised 
durenberger they would not prejudge his case which the panel has 
spent more than a year investigating 
the theory expounded by some that the committee will because 
of the current political climate take harsh action against senator 
durenberger in order to prove that it is tough is ludicrous said 
committee vice chairman sen warren rudman rnh 
if the facts warrant the committee will recommend strong 
sanctions but if they do not we will not rudman said in 
opening remarks at the hearing 
durenberger sat between his attorney and an aide at a table 
facing committee members his back to around 100 onlookers and 
several tables full of reporters 
the committees special counsel robert bennett later opened 
his case by saying that durenberger knowingly and actively used 
a book promotion scheme to circumvent senate honoraria limits and 
divert 100000 in speaking fees into his own pocket 
this is unethical this is not honest said bennett who was 
expected to take most of the day laying out his case 
one of durenbergers four sons dan 22 asked his father during 
a hearing break how are you 
perfect his father replied 
bennett is familiar with the role of prosecutor having brought 
the case in 1981 against thensen harrison a williams jr 
dnj the last senator to face these kinds of hearings 
durenberger spent monday polishing an opening statement to the 
committee to give a context to the defense by his attorney 
said press secretary lois west 
the senator is represented by jim hamilton a former counsel to 
the senate watergate committee 
durenberger who has been silent on the case in recent days 
apologized to minnesotans last december for mistakes and lapses 
in judgment 
but the intense public scrutiny of his finances could spell the 
end of his career if voters in minnesota a state known for clean 
government arent satisfied with his defense 
many public radio stations in minnesota will broadcast the 
hearings live and television stations are planning heavy daily 
coverage 
people are concluding that something is seriously wrong 
said william luther the minneapolis attorney whose complaint 
initiated the senate investigation now its a matter of seeing 
if any kind of reasonable evidence or defense is presented 
durenberger does not have to run for reelection until 1994 but 
opinion polls indicate a majority of minnesotans think he should 
resign if the committee finds serious violations 
the sixmember ethics committee is made up equally of 
republicans and democrats it will decide after the hearings 
whether its allegations are true and then recommend a punishment to 
the full senate ranging from a mild reprimand to expulsion 
bennett recommended removing williams from the senate after the 
1981 hearings but he resigned before his colleagues had to vote on 
ousting him the ethics committee began its investigation after 
williams had already been convicted in federal court in the abscam 
bribery case 
the committee began investigating durenberger early last year 
and brought charges against him in february and again in may 
the first set of allegations focused on the book contract 
durenberger used to earn 100000 in speaking fees in 1985 and 1986 
for promoting two books he wrote on defense and health issues 
in may the panel charged that durenberger abused his office and 
misused public funds in a pattern of improper conduct involving 
his minneapolis condominium 
durenberger has acknowledged that he tried to cut the cost of 
maintaining homes in washington and minnesota by claiming senate 
reimbursement for nights he stayed in the condominium 
