<TEXT>
the house on monday approved a 10 million 
research program to develop new technologies and inspection 
programs to find defects in airplanes before they cause accidents 
the bill by rep tom lewis rfla was passed on a voice vote 
with no opposition a similar plan is being considered in the 
senate commerce science and transportation committee 
the legislation was prompted by the crash landing last july of a 
united airlines dc10 at sioux city iowa and an april 1988 
accident in which part of the top was ripped off an aloha airlines 
plane during a short interisland flight 
the national transportation safety board said both accidents 
could have been prevented through adequate inspection and 
maintenance programs 
for example the united crash landing in which 112 of the 296 
aboard were killed was caused by an engine failure due to a crack 
in a fan disk from a defect when the dc10 was manufactured in 1971 
the section of the aloha airliner was ripped off as the result 
of cracks in the outer metal covering that began almost 17 years 
earlier but went undetected the ntsb said 
in both cases the federal aviation administration began 
mandating inspections of aging airliners for such defects and 
cracks only after the accidents 
the status quo for too long has been to do something about a 
problem only after it costs lives lewis said 
the bill would require the faa to devote 10 million of its 
research over the next three years to addressing the risks of 
component failures and coming up with a program to prevent them 
</TEXT>
