<TEXT>
five states sued mobil chemical co on tuesday 
charging the company falsely claimed its hefty trash bags and 
grocery bags would decompose 
mobil announced in march that it would stop referring to its 
hefty bags as biodegradable because of confusion about what 
degradable means 
lawsuits were filed by massachusetts minnesota texas 
california and wisconsin new york and washington state were also 
expected to file lawsuits 
the lawsuits contend mobil made false claims for the hefty bags 
in advertisements by saying they break down when exposed to sun 
wind and rain 
allen gray a spokesman for mobil chemical said the company had 
been talking with states and had hoped to resolve questions about 
its claims without a lawsuit 
were disappointed here he said and noted that the company 
already voluntarily agreed to drop its claims for bags because 
there is no agreement on how to define the term biodegradable 
the massachusetts lawsuit said the degradability claim violated 
the state consumer protection act the bags do not perform as 
promised because they are ultimately incinerated or disposed of in 
landfills where they decompose no faster than ordinary plastic 
bags the lawsuit alleges 
promoting plastics as degradable may actually cause consumers 
to increase the amount of their litter because they may believe 
that the products will degrade rapidly if littered said the 
lawsuit filed in superior court at suffolk county 
in march gray said claims that the bags degrade in sunlight had 
been fully substantiated by tests and that the company never said 
the bags would be the answer to the countrys waste disposal 
problem 
the company said it would continue to make hefty trash bags with 
an environmentally safe additive that speeds up their 
decomposition when exposed to sunlight 
gray conceded that if left out in arizona somewhere as bag 
with the additive can quickly decompose in a couple of months but 
in a northern climate like chicago it could take well over a year 
mobil made its announcement shortly before it was to meet with a 
task force of state attorney generals investigating deceptive 
advertising and packaging 
massachusetts is seeking civil penalties of 5000 for each 
violation of the state consumer protection act in massachusetts 
mobil sold or distributed an estimated 112000 cases of hefty bags 
and more than 75 million marketote grocery sacks between june and 
december of 1989 according to the lawsuit 
tom mcnaught a spokesman for state attorney general james 
shannon said the state also wanted assurances that mobil has 
permanently dropped the degradability references 
minnesota is seeking 250000 in damages 
unfortunately mobils advertising claims break down faster 
than their garbage bags said minnesota attorney general hubert 
humphrey iii at a news conference in st paul minn 
the california lawsuit seeks civil penalties of 500000 and an 
injunction to formally halt the ads 
in wisconsin attorney general don hanaway said these claims 
prey on peoples desire to play a role in protecting the 
environment 
hefty bags need to be exposed to a minimum of 26 to 42 days of 
sunlight in arizona or florida and up to six months in other parts 
of the united states to trigger degradation of the bags according 
to the lawsuits 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

