<TEXT>
the house in the face of an administration 
veto threat voted overwhelmingly tuesday to send president bush a 
bill allowing federal workers to take an active role in politics 
for the first time in half a century 
by a 33487 vote the house forfeited its own version of hatch 
act changes to adopt a senate bill that is less onerous to the 
white house but is still opposed by top administration officials 
ninety of the 176 republicans including minority leader robert 
h michel of illinois joined 244 democrats to pass the bill three 
democrats reps anthony beilenson of california charles bennett 
of florida and thomas foglietta of pennsylvania voted against the 
measure 
unlike the original house bill approved more than a year ago 
the measure that being sent to bush retains prohibitions against 
federal workers running for partisan office or soliciting campaign 
funds from the public 
the senate passed the same bill last month by a vote of 6730 
but gop leaders there have expressed confidence they can persuade 
one or two of their colleagues to change votes to sustain a veto 
attorney general dick thornburgh said in a letter tuesday that 
he and other senior bush advisers would recommend that the 
president veto the bill 
such a reversal in the role of partisan politics in the ethic 
of public service would permit virtually unbridled partisan 
activities by federal employees thornburgh said in a letter to 
house gop whip newt gingrich of georgia 
as passed by both houses the bill substantially erases 
prohibitions under the 51yearold hatch law that restrict th 
nations 3 million federal civil service and postal employees to 
little more than voting 
if enacted into law those employees could begin holding office 
in local state and national political party organizations for the 
first time they also could solicit campaign funds from coworkers 
on behalf of federal employee union political action committees 
but only when not working 
however federal workers would still be prohibited from running 
in a partisan election for public office or soliciting campaign 
funds from anyone other than fellow members of government employee 
unions 
the original house version approved by a 29790 vote in april 
1989 would have allowed government workers to take leaves of 
absence to run for partisan office and solicit campaign funds from 
anyone 
government workers in the soviet union enjoy more freedom to 
practice politics than americas government workers said rep 
william ford dmich one of the bills sponsors 
we are not advocating the gray masses rising up in a 
coup ford said were only asking for the simple right to put 
up a yard sign display a bumper sticker send a check or stuff 
envelopes 
the hatch act was enacted at the height of the new deal to 
protect the emerging civil service from being coerced by political 
appointees to contribute to or work on behalf of candidates 
the americans who guide the planes we fly and who deliver 
the mail deserve our trust in the very modest right to participate 
in the political process said rep gerry sikorski dminn 
opponents argue that the laws protections against a spoils 
system are still needed 
times have changed but the factors that make the hatch act 
necessary have not changed said rep frank wolf rva human 
nature has not been repealed by congress the inevitable result 
will be a politicizing of the federal work force 
</TEXT>
