claims 
the consent agreement with the federal trade commission is 
without admission of any wrongdoing said terry kelley a 
spokesman for sterling drug inc which makes midol 
kelley said the company the nations largest manufacturer of 
overthecounter menstrual relief medicine entered into the 
agreement to avoid protracted costly litigation 
it would have involved highly technical scientific issues 
said kelley 
this does not involve our current advertising kelley said 
explaining that all of the questionable advertising had been 
stopped by march sterling will continue to manufacture and 
market the midol brand products 
the ftc said sterling had violated a 1985 order prohibiting a 
firm from making performance claims unless it has a reasonable 
basis to substantiate the claims 
the complaint said sterling ran certain ads for original 
formula midol and maximum strength midol for cramps from 
march 1985 to january 1986 and in april 1988 that claimed or 
implied one of the ingredients was a muscle relaxant for menstrual 
cramps that would quickly help relieve muscle contractions 
the company did not have competent and reliable scientific 
evidence for those claims the agency said in its complaint 
the ingredient in question has been removed from the 
product according to sterling 
virtually all of the companys products were included in the 
ftcs advertising complaint 
also cited were ads for maximum strength midol pms which 
claimed total or complete relief for the symptoms of 
premenstrual syndrome 
the ftc also said the company had no competent and reliable 
scientific evidence for claims that original midol mutisymptom 
formula and maximum strength midol multisymptom formula 
relieved menstrual bloating and waterweight gain 
sterling is based in new york city and is a whollyowned 
subsidiary of the eastmankodak co 
