<TEXT>
climbing the corporate ladder can plunge some 
people into depression but an early diagnosis could spare middle 
managers a serious case of the office blues researchers said 
tuesday 
a study of 1870 whitecollar employees of westinghouse electric 
corp in monroeville a pittsburgh suburb showed 166 percent of 
female and 86 percent of male managers were clinically depressed 
in the year prior to the survey which was taken in 1987 and 1988 
the figures exceed the latest depression rate for all americans 
44 percent in 1986 according to the national institute of mental 
health 
the bottom line for you is that depression is eminently 
treatable said dr david kupfer chairman of the psychiatry 
department at the university of pittsburgh the research findings 
were presented to about 100 personnel directors healthinsurance 
managers and corporate doctors at a conference on mental health 
thirtysix percent of female and 23 percent of male westinghouse 
managers qualified as clinically depressed at some point during 
their lives the study said 
according to the american psychiatric association a person 
suffers from major depression when he or she shows at least five of 
the following symptoms within a twoweek period irregular sleeping 
patterns irregular eating habits recurrent thoughts of suicide or 
death depressed mood loss of interest or pleasure in daily 
activities significant weight loss or gain agitated or retarded 
movements feelings of worthlessness or guilt and lack of 
concentration 
at least one of the symptoms must be a depressed mood or loss of 
interest or pleasure the apa says 
herbert freudenberger a new york city psychologist and 
consultant to companies on whitecollar stress and depression said 
the westinghouse study is significant because it marks the first 
time a large company allowed such an examination of its workers 
westinghouse employs about 120000 people worldwide 
midlevel managers often are depressed because they find 
themselves trapped between the gripes of their subordinates and 
demands of their own bosses he said 
the firstline managers are the ones who get hell from over 
them and hell from under them said dr e carroll curtis 
westinghouses medical director 
pitt and westinghouse interviewed the managers most of whom 
were white males under a grant from the national institute of 
mental health 
the most common causes of depression at work were lack of 
rewards a cloudy job future and specific events such as pay cuts 
or bad evaluations the study said 
the most common cause of depression at home was a spouse with a 
history of psychiatric disorders the study said 
mark kamlet an economics professor at carnegie mellon 
university estimated that depressionrelated absenteeism lost 
wages hospital costs prescriptions and suicides will cost the 
us economy 369 billion in 1990 
researchers said companies could train more executives and 
managers to spot depressions symptoms and tactfully address the 
illness with employees 
the westinghouse study said although depression usually can be 
treated without hospitalization 70 percent of the depressed 
managers didnt seek treatment 
its not preferred procedure for a manager to turn himself in 
to any psychologist kamlet said 
particularly with males someone will tell you to buck up and 
take a few shots of beer then youll be all right said jim 
jefferson 43 a mellon bank building manager who recently returned 
to work after treatment for depression but he said it doesnt 
work that way 
</TEXT>
