<TEXT>
president joaquin 
balaguer made it just another day at the office tuesday without 
acknowledging that official results indicated he narrowly won a 
sixth term as president 
no rallies were held and no victory speeches were made following 
mondays declaration by the central electoral board that the 
83yearold blind balaguer had defeated 80yearold leftist 
challenger juan bosch by a margin of fewer than 25000 votes in the 
may 16 election 
a review of balloting results caused the almost monthlong delay 
in concluding the election results 
the board reported balaguer had received 678268 votes or 357 
percent to 653423 or 344 percent for bosch 
under dominican law balaguer will not be proclaimed 
presidentelect until the board rules on all vote challenges a 
process that took almost two months in the last four elections 
inauguration for a fouryear term is set for aug 16 
two opposition parties filed formal challenges with the board 
tuesday charging irregularities and fraud in the electoral 
process such challenges are routine in the dominican republic but 
are generally regarded as a technicality and rarely result in 
significant changes in the results 
boschs dominican liberation party called a meeting for 
wednesday evening to determine its course of action 
thousands of candles twinkled in workingclass neighborhoods in 
a symbol of protest after the boards figures were announced on 
television police arrested 140 people for disturbing the peace by 
lighting candles or chanting antibalaguer slogans but most 
detainees were quickly released 
the electoral board said 408 percent of the 32 million 
registered voters stayed home on election day the highest 
abstention figure in any election since dictator gen rafael 
leonidas trujillo was assassinated in 1961 
bosch a former president was overthrown by a military coup in 
1963 
balaguer was a figuerhead president during the 31year trujillo 
dictatorship he was first elected president in 1966 and served 
three consecutive terms before losing in 1978 he was reelected in 
1986 
he appeared to be in trouble before the election because of this 
caribbean island countrys economic crisis frequent electricity 
blackouts and water shortages opinion polls had bosch leading by 
up to 10 points 
bosch is a marxist but says he is not a communist and 
recognizes capitalism as necessary for reviving the dominican 
economy 
</TEXT>
