<TEXT>
at least half of algerias voters 
apparently heeded an election boycott call tuesday as the ruling 
party battled islamic fundamentalists in the first contested ballot 
since french rule ended in 1962 observers said 
a majority of district races appeared dominated by the national 
liberation front the nations sole political party until last 
years constitutional reforms 
the fundamentalist islamic salvation front the only other major 
party on the ballot benefitted by the withdrawal of several groups 
that urged a boycott 
official results were expected wednesday 
boycott leaders claimed the election was rigged in favor of the 
ruling party because it controls nearly all the media has greater 
resources than other parties and has its functionaries in local 
government offices where the votes will be counted 
charges of voterigging surfaced immediately after the polls 
closed at 7 pm 
the interior ministry said 55 percent of the 13 million eligible 
voters went to the polls but figures showed a considerable range 
from 73 percent in the town of eltarf to 16 percent in the berber 
town of tiziouzou 
fifteen thousand seats were contested in this north african 
nations 1541 municipal councils and 48 provinces in all 11 
parties were on the ballot 
hocine ait ahmed leader of the opposition berber movement the 
front of socialist forces and former president ahmed ben bellas 
movement for democracy in algeria led the boycott effort 
police were deployed throughout the country as the official 
media urged algerians to vote in this first test of democracy 
fundamentalist leader abassi madani a philosophy teacher 
predicted several days ago his party would capture 75 percent of 
the vote he challenged the legitimacy of the election in advance 
if the result failed to reflect this figure 
the statement was denounced as a troublemaking provocation 
by several hundred fellow university professors and lecturers 
for months fundamentalist supporters have been accused of 
harrassing single women and disrupting nightclubs in the algiers 
region prompting denunciations from most political groups 
in the algiers suburb of el harrach the national liberation 
front withdrew from the elections accusing the fundamentalists of 
exercising moral violence against the voters and committing 
serious violations against the election law the statement did 
not elaborate 
the official news agency reported several groups of islamic 
supporters tried to overrun some algiers voting stations alleging 
the vote counting was influenced by the government 
numerous voters in the algiers district were turned away from 
polling booths when they appeared without the necessary documents 
among those blocked were men who tried to exercise their right to 
vote on behalf of their wife or wives without written 
authorization 
the national liberation fronts was forced to give up its 
monopoly on power after soldiers killed scores of people in october 
1988 riots sparked by deteriorating economic conditions 
constitutional changes adopted in february 1989 legalized pluralism 
the islamic salvation front seeks to establish the islamic legal 
code the sharia as law and openly opposes the democratic process 
