<TEXT>
congress has been unable to agree on 
comprehensive oil spill legislation over provisions on ship 
construction and liability two problems exemplified in the wreck 
of a norwegian supertanker officials said tuesday 
since 1975 congress has struggled to create a liability and 
response law that covers the estimated 8000 oil spills that occur 
in the united states annually 
galvanized by the exxon valdez accident both the house and 
senate last fall passed sweeping legislation but the approximately 
100 members of a housesenate conference committee have met only 
once to resolve differences in the bills 
last weekend the supertanker mega borg caught fire 57 miles 
from galveston and since then firefighters have struggled to bring 
the fire under control 
the fire prompted members of congress on tuesday in calling for 
conferees to step up the pace 
once again the need to prevent these spills is made all too 
clear said sen brock adams 
the bill creates a 1 billion cleanup fund through a 5cent tax 
on each barrel of oil created in or imported to the united states 
it also establishes coast guard oil spill response centers along 
us coasts 
but the house and senate disagree on requiring supertankers to 
have double hulls and using international protocol to guide 
liability in a spill 
congressional staff members say conferees are close to resolving 
the double hull issue but international protocol and its 
relationship to state liability laws has tripped up oil spill 
legislation for the past seven congresses officials say 
senators led by majority leader george mitchell say liability 
limits set by international protocol arent strict enough 
they see it rightly as a back door attempt to preempt state 
laws said mike matz of the sierra club nineteen states require 
unlimited liability for the oil companies or carriers to clean up 
damage to the environment 
international protocols provide up to 260 million from an 
international compensation fund before any us dollars are spent 
on an cleanup say house backers 
and they must be in place for the united states to hold foreign 
vessels liable for spills that could affect us water they say 
currently the norwegian owners of the mega borg could walk away 
from liability for damage the wreck causes the us shoreline 
because the fire occurred in international waters 
were living on the good graces of the norwegians right now 
said rep billy tauzin dla a house conferee and proponent of 
the international protocol i hope this incident drives the 
senate to reconsider 
but mitchell said full compensation for catastrophic spills 
cannot be obtained from international protocol limits 
he said the house version for instance would have limited 
exxons liability for last years alaskan spill to less than 60 
million damage from the valdez spill is estimated to be more than 
2 billion said mitchell dmaine 
exxons victims could not have obtained more than 260 million 
from the international regime and 1 billion from the federal trust 
fund if this bill had been enacted mitchell said of the house 
version 
but rep jack fields who flew over the mega borg fire monday 
said the accident clearly begs for acceptance of international 
protocols 
states like maine want to punish the shippers said fields 
rtexas they want to be able to squeeze as much blood from the 
turnip as possible rather than make those who have been damaged 
whole 
the house bill requires new oil tankers to have double hulls and 
existing tankers to be retrofitted in 15 years the senate 
recommends study of double hulls or better means to prevent oil 
spills 
</TEXT>
