because he was inattentive and unwise hamilton said but the 
attorney did not specify any punishment the lowest form of 
punishment would be a mild letter of rebuke 
bennett who earlier told the committee that durenberger 
exhibited very serious insensitivity to the ethical demands of 
his office told senators they should denounce sen durenberger 
publicly for knowingly engaging in unethical conduct which has 
brought dishonor and disrepute to this institution 
the hearing took on the aura of a trial as the 12year senator 
stared from across the room when bennett standing at a lectern 
accused durenberger of making fake promotional appearances in 1985 
and 1986 for his two books 
the speeches were really a gimmick to magically turn 
honoraria earned from appearances before trade groups into book 
promotions allowing durenberger to make 100000 beyond his senate 
salary and exceed the chambers speakingfee limits bennett said 
the scheme was concocted bennett said as the senator neared 
the legal maximum for honoraria 
bennett said durenbergers attempts to change ownership of his 
minneapolis condominium was a scheme to improperly collect 40055 
in senate travel reimbursements from 1983 through 1989 he would 
not have been eligible for the payments if he had owned the 
residence outright bennett said 
the senator consistently engaged in a pattern of unethical 
conduct and showed very serious insensitivity to the ethical 
demands of his office bennett told the sixmember committee 
about 200 spectators attended the first of the hearings which 
the committee will use to determine if durenberger broke the 
chambers rules and federal law 
the panel has found substantial credible evidence that 
durenberger may have committed violations in the condominium deal 
the book arrangement and the limousine trips 
if the panel finds wrongdoing it can recommend that the senate 
punish durenberger by handing out anything from a mild rebuke to 
expulsion although the latter is unlikely 
in his book deal durenberger received 100000 from a 
minneapolis publisher piranha press in return for addressing 
trade groups that sent their speaking fees to piranha 
durenberger contended the speeches were made to promote books 
but bennett said the real purpose was for the senator to collect 
honoraria in excess of senate limits 22530 in 1985 and 30040 
in 1986 
this very hungry fish piranha press was allowed to engage in 
a feeding frenzy to make money bennett said durenberger he 
added allowed himself and his office to be used as the bait and 
he got 100000 for his trouble 
the scheme made a large profit for piranha which earned 
248360 from durenbergers speeches and only 15560 from the sale 
of books 
in calling the book arrangement a scam bennett told the 
committee that in the 113 appearances being investigated the host 
groups thought they were hearing a typical honoraria speech some 
of the groups strenuously objected when they learned 
durenbergers speech was classified as a book promotion and 
withdrew the invitation 
in addition bennett said the two books durenberger wrote on 
national security and health issues were displayed at only three of 
the 113 appearances at one appearance durenberger commented 
this is a book but what it really is is 44 speeches compiled 
into a book 
in describing the complicated condominium deal bennett said 
durenberger wouldnt have been able to collect senate travel 
reimbursements if he had owned the residence 
so durenberger schemed not once but twice to have business 
partnerships take ownership and lease the condominium back to him 
when he stayed there thus allowing senate travel expenses to be 
paid 
when the original partner decided to end the initial partnership 
in 1987 four years after it was formed durenberger entered into a 
similar arrangement year with his former campaign manager 
