<TEXT>
two environmental groups have filed a 
lawsuit to prevent the restart of the savannah river nuclear 
weapons plant on the grounds it would violate the federal clean 
water act an attorney said tuesday 
the lawsuit was filed monday in us district court in columbia 
by the natural resources defense council and the energy research 
foundation 
the groups charge that hot water discharges from one of three 
reactors scheduled to restart in december would exceed temperature 
limits set by the 1972 clean water act 
the discharges would send scalding water into the small streams 
adjacent to the plant said jimmy chandler attorney for the energy 
research foundation 
this hot water discharge will wipe out virtually all aquatic 
life and all vegetation within the receiving streams chandler 
said it will cause a loss of 10 to 12 acres of forested wetlands 
each year 
the reactor will discharge water at between 150 degrees and 170 
degrees while federal law prohibits hot water discharges of more 
than 90 degress he said 
us department of energy spokesman tim tomastik whose 
organization owns the savannah river site refused to comment on 
the lawsuit because the issue was in litigation the government has 
60 days to respond 
the reactors located near aiken near the georgia line were 
closed in 1988 after an accident at one unit raised questions about 
safety standards and the risk of mechanical failures more than 1 
billion is being spent to upgrade the reactors and retrain workers 
the plant produces tritium a radioactive isotope of hydrogen 
used to make hbombs tritiums decays at a rate of 55 percent a 
year meaning quantities in warheads must be replenished the 
government says its stockpile of tritium is running low although 
information about tritium inventories is classified 
in may energy secretary james d watkins announced a tentative 
schedule providing for the restart of the k reactor in december 
however a cooling tower that would lower the temperature of 
discharged water is not scheduled for completion until 1992 
the lawsuit filed monday asks that the k reactor not be operated 
until the cooling tower is completed 
restarting k reactor is unsafe and unnecessary said frances 
hart local coordinator of the energy research foundation a 
private nonprofit environmentalist group its time the 
government started obeying its own laws 
</TEXT>
