<TEXT>
an investigator has 
recommended modifications to a boeing aircraft after blaming a fire 
in the cargo section for the crash of a south african airways jet 
the 1987 crash near mauritius killed all 159 people aboard 
sabotage was ruled out in the report by justice cecil margo in 
newspapers tuesday but no cause could be determined for the fire in 
the boeing 747200 combi 
the plane en route from taipei taiwan to johannesburg 
plunged into the indian ocean about 1500 miles east of 
johannesburg on nov 28 1987 most of the passengers on flight 295 
were japanese taiwanese or south african 
margo called for changes in the combi configuration planes that 
have an extralarge cargo hold on the same level as the passenger 
section and cockpit 
he said smoke and gasses spread quickly through the passenger 
section and possibly the cockpit plastic and cardboard packing 
were involved in the blaze according to the investigation report 
there was a strong possibility gases and smoke overwhelmed 
the flight crew the report said 
margos report said the smokedetection firefighting equipment 
and safety procedures on the plane were inadequate 
until such problems are corrected the combi configuration 
with passengers and cargo on the same deck should be prohibited 
as creating an unacceptable risk margo said 
he said the us national transportation safety board had 
rejected his recommendation for modifications to the plane but the 
us federal aviation administration had issued new directives to 
minimize fire hazards on the combi 
south african airways has since removed the cargo section from 
the passenger level on its one remaining combi 
jack gamble spokesman for boeing commercial airplane group in 
renton wash said company officials had not seen the judges 
report 
