<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
june 411 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
most north american newsprint producers 
increased prices about 5 percent in june the first broad hike in 
more than two years but buyers say theyll resist paying it 
because of plentiful supplies 
industry analysts and purchasers say the 35 increase which 
raised the benchmark eastern us list price of standard newsprint 
to 685 a metric ton hinges mainly on whether labor negotiations 
are settled at mills in eastern canada the worlds largest single 
source of newsprint 
the labor dispute is probably the only thing thats keeping 
the price increase in place now said dan dowis director of 
newsprint for knightridder inc one of the nations largest 
newspaper groups 
if the negotiations are settled without a strike youll see a 
lot of the increase going back to purchasers in the form of 
discounts or even rollbacks on whats being paid now dowis said 
our policy is that we wont pay the increased price 
the price hike which went into effect june 1 was first 
announced in february by abitibiprice inc of toronto the worlds 
secondlargest newsprint maker behind fletcher challenge of new 
zealand 
it is the first since an industrywide increase of 66 percent on 
jan 1 1988 and producers say the hike is overdue because of 
declining profits that have left them struggling at the margin 
threatening mill shutdowns 
sellers have been getting killed all the canadians who are 
twothirds of the north american market are making no money 
because theyre selling at 525 a ton and thats their cost to 
produce said mark kurland an analyst with mabon nugent in new 
york 
newsprint is now sold at about a 19 percent discount from the 
list price the increase raises actual transaction prices to about 
555560 a metric ton from about 525 
newspaper companies have been stockpiling inventories of about 
50 days in anticipation of a possible strike at canadian mills 
which have already begun to cut production 
the industry is closely watching talks that began may 31 between 
montrealbased stone consolidated inc and the canadian 
paperworkers union which is seeking wage increases of 8 percent a 
year in each of two years 
a strike at stone which would likely spread to the entire 
industry would sharply curtail supplies it also could force the 
shutdown of some canadian mills which already face the prospect of 
a costly retooling from virgin pulp to recycled production 
the increase will go through for now if stone settles then 
newsprint purchasers will have the upper hand and it will probably 
argue against the increase holding said kurland 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the citys two newspapers decided june 8 
to dissolve their joint operating agreement ending a lawsuit filed 
by the morning knoxville newssentinel against the afternoon 
knoxville journal 
under the joa the newssentinel provided sales production and 
distribution for the journal editorial departments of the two 
newspapers are separate 
the lawsuit claimed that the journals owner persis corp 
violated terms of the agreement when it purchased the daily times 
in nearby maryville last year journal editor and publisher gerald 
garcia was made president and publisher of the daily times 
the newssentinel which recently began a zoned edition in 
maryville considered the daily times a direct competitor 
the lawsuit contended that with garcia in the dual roles the 
daily times would have access to the newssentinels confidential 
business information and trade secrets 
the arrangement to end the joa calls for the newssentinel to 
pay persis 40 million in two 20 million installments the money 
will be in lieu of payments the journal would have received from 
dec 31 1991 through the scheduled end of the agreement on dec 
31 2005 
the plan calls for the joa to end in december 1991 until then 
the newssentinel will continue to act as agent on some business 
matters for the journal 
the newssentinel owned by the ew scripps co has a daily 
circulation of 101000 and a sunday circulation of 169000 the 
journal publishes monday through saturday with a circulation of 
40000 
</TEXT>
