<TEXT>
business people know the value of entertaining their clients 
over a few drinks and a sumptuous meal in a relaxed setting its a 
cost of forging working relationships 
and no one does it better than the special interests influencing 
state legislators in the 50 state capitols wining and dining goes 
with lobbying as easily as gin mixes with vermouth 
the entertainment with legislators is the most important part 
of our business it is the wrench to the plumber said new mexico 
lobbyist edwin t mahr he estimated 80 percent of the 1 million 
his firm spent in 198789 went for such entertainment 
lobbyists and lawmakers insist votes arent exchanged for meals 
but critics say special interests get special attention at the 
expense of the public interest 
in a 50state look at lobbying the associated press found a 
crazyquilt of laws that lacks significant oversight and fails to 
give an accurate national picture of how much special interests 
spend on entertaining and which lawmakers they spend it on 
getting to know the people who pass change or kill legislation 
is vital for lobbyists hoping to persuade them to take the side of 
their special interest 
there could be nothing worse for a lobbyist than not to be 
recognized said melvin cooper executive director of the alabama 
ethics commission 
theyre selling ideas just like somebody else is selling a 
car said jan konesey of delaware common cause a group that 
itself lobbies for laws to make government more open to public 
view when lobbyists go out to dinner with legislators or play 
golf with them or take them to a football game youre just 
building relationships that make you a better salesman 
whether those contacts go too far is another matter and voters 
have little to go on other than the word of legislators and 
lobbyists that there isnt undue influence 
four states require no reporting by lobbyists of their spending 
at all and only 31 of the remaining 46 require lobbyists to break 
down spending into categories such as entertainment 
however the 31 states have thresholds whereby a lawmaker being 
entertained doesnt have to be identified unless the amount spent 
is above a set amount in arizona for example lobbyists dont 
have to list separate expenses if they spend less then 25 for each 
issue they discuss with a legislator so a lobbyist could buy a 
lawmaker a 74 meal and not have to disclose it if they talked 
about three issues 
the people who get hurt are those who are not at the table 
and thats usually the taxpayer there is this insiders game that 
is almost exclusionary of the public said chuck sauvage of 
common cause in washington state which itself lobbies for more 
accountability by those who make and influence laws 
some states are considering tighter rules 
on june 6 california voters overwhelmingly passed an 
ethicsingovernment measure among other things it prohibits 
lawmakers from accepting speaking fees and requires the legislature 
to bar or strictly limit gifts to elected officials 
and the public in general has strong opinions about 
accountability 
in a media generalassociated press poll 75 percent of 1071 
adults across the nation said gifts from lobbyists create undue 
influence eight in 10 said lawmakers sometimes vote the way 
lobbyists want them to in exchange for gifts 
eight in 10 said they would back a disclosure law requiring 
lobbyists to publicly report all contacts they have with state 
lawmakers 
contacts pay off nebraska sen ernie chambers contends 
there have always been those senators who have gone to the 
trough with a glad heart the free meals the free booze and the 
free whatever else they could get chambers said and then they 
say that this is just business that it doesnt buy their vote or 
influence them unduly bull 
florida rep ron glickman said lobbyists have natural 
advantages because they have things members want financial 
contributions and gifts it may not be direct trade but theres a 
feeling of good will when an issue comes up for a vote theyll 
say we helped you its time for you to help 
lobbyists do expect something in return for their hospitality 
even if its not an outright exchange said kirby hendee a retired 
lobbyist and former state senator in wisconsin 
if you buy a guy enough meals and buy him enough drinks hes 
going to vote your way over time you cant repeal human nature 
hendee said 
the special interests decry the notion that the way to a 
lawmakers vote is through his stomach 
if you can buy him for a steak and a martini he wasnt worth 
the time of having dinner with said victor condello a partner 
in a new york lobbying firm that makes more than 1 million 
annually 
but lobbyists who dont have deep pockets appreciate the value 
of wining and dining 
the problem is access if you cant afford to wine and dine 
one feels lost said phil kaplan who lobbies on behalf of the 
poor in olympia wash 
and access is the name of the game 
to me access is the most important thing in the world said 
john larson chairman of the california fair political practices 
commission my god you give me two hours with the president of 
the united states thats all the access i would need 
not all entertaining is done at the dinner table 
in new mexico lobbyist truett gill spent 300 to stock snack 
items for house leaders in 1989 
utahs 29 senators and their families were invited to spend a 
free weekend at the deer valley ski resort last year and most them 
accepted while considering a tax exemption for capital 
improvements at ski areas the first attempt to pass the bill 
failed although a modified version later passed 
florida has a lobbyist known as the beer fairy a legislator 
announces he wants to have a party and someone leaves cases of 
beer anonymously at the doorstep 
florida lawmakers and their families also are offered a free 
trip to disney world every year at a cost of 200 to 2000 per 
lawmaker lawmakers recently passed a bill to prohibit customers 
from selling unused entrance tickets to the theme park but house 
rules chairman fred lippman said the trip had no bearing on his 
vote 
mickey minnie and goofy sure as hell dont convince us what 
to do with disney world lippman said 
