<TEXT>
brooding hulking towering 
fearsome wonderfully cavernous superbly sinister 
frighteningly big and mean 
these are some of the terrible things opera critics like to say 
about finnish bass matti salminen their words apply as well to his 
giantsize voice as to his menacing 6foot5 figure 
when i was young my voice was smaller and more lyrical 
salminen 45 said in a recent interview but i studied and 
worked hard and it grew 
thats an understatement as anyone can attest who has heard his 
thundering tones easily penetrate the 4000seat metropolitan opera 
house 
he was much in evidence there this spring singing in all four 
operas of wagners ring cycle he was the greedy giant fafner in 
das rheingold the cuckolded husband hunding in die 
walkuere fafner again in siegfried this time transformed 
into a sleeping dragon who is first awakened and then slain by the 
title character expiring to music that is so beautiful just 
like a schubert song and the villainous hagen who gives 
siegfried and bruennhilde a rough time of it in die 
goetterdaemmerung 
the last role is by far the biggest and most challenging 
hagens personality is vicious from the ground up but he is 
one of the most interesting characters in the whole ring 
salminen said even though he doesnt appear in the earlier 
operas his appearance is being built up to from the start 
hagen is the illegitimate son of alberich the dwarf whose theft 
of gold from the rhinemaidens causes all the trouble to begin with 
alberich loses his treasure to wotan king of the gods and spends 
the rest of the cycle scheming to get it back where the cringing 
cowardly father fails the daring dastardly son almost succeeds 
from alberichs weakness all of a sudden comes a strong 
figure salminen said he manipulates everyone he has 
incredible slyness 
salminen plays hagen to the hilt his voice brims with malice as 
he plots to ruin the heroic lovers and insinuates his way into 
their confidence the pleasure he takes in his own scheming is 
evident from the gleam in his eye and the way he struts about the 
stage its a performance that has earned him unanimous raves from 
the reviewers 
his hagen will be one of the highlights of the public 
broadcasting services telecast of the mets ring cycle 
production on four consecutive nights june 1821 he also will be 
heard as fafner but hunding will be sung by german bass kurt moll 
wagner has played a major part in salminens career he first 
came to international prominence in 1976 as hunding and the giant 
fasolt at the centennial production by patrice chereau at bayreuth 
west germany 
his met debut was a triumph in the role of king marke in 
wagners tristan und isolde whose 20minute monologue usually 
puts audiences to sleep last season he sang daland in wagners 
der fliegende hollaender he has also performed such 
nonwagnerian parts as the comic villain osmin in mozarts 
abduction from the seraglio and rocco the jailer in beethovens 
fidelio 
yet it rankles him that his met career is not more varied in 
europe he gets to portray the title role in mussorgskys boris 
godunov and phillip ii in verdis don carlos 
the met tells me they really only want me for the german 
repertory salminen said with a sigh here im allowed to sing 
ramfis the priest in verdis aida but thats not much 
compensation 
salminen who is married and has two children has a home in 
zurich switzerland and also one in helsinki finland 
he grew up in the town of turko where at age 17 he won an 
amateur singing contest four years later he was singing in the 
finnish national opera chorus and appearing there in small roles 
such as charles v in don carlos and monterone in rigoletto 
in 1969 he went to rome to study with vocal coach luigi ricci and 
his career took off in the early 1970s 
he is just one of several finnish singers who have made names 
for themselves abroad in recent years others include baritone 
jorma hynninen soprano karita mattila and the late bass martti 
talvela whom salminen mourns as a father figure to all us 
finnish singers 
salminen said part of the reason they were driven to seek 
international careers was the lack of a finnish opera house 
suitable for major productions 
in a country of 5 million people we have had only one tiny 
house that with great trouble could squeeze maybe six or eight 
violins into the orchestra pit he said so if you wanted to do 
something you had to go outside 
he now sings every summer at the savonlinna festival in finland 
and looks forward to being involved with a new national opera house 
scheduled to open in helsinki in 1993 
he will not appear at the met next season but will be back in 
199192 for ramfis daland rocco osmin and the commendatore in 
mozarts don giovanni 
</TEXT>
