<TEXT>
a freetrade pact between the united states 
and mexico should spur an increase in investment in mexico and make 
the country a potent competitor to the newly industrialized 
countries of asia analysts said 
figures recently issued by the us department of labor showed 
that in 1987 the most recent year for which overall figures were 
available it cost manufacturers 157 an hour to hire a worker in 
mexico that compared with 179 in south korea 212 in hong 
kong 231 in singapore and 1340 in this country 
in addition to low wages mexicos proximity to the united 
states gives it an advantage over asian and european competitors in 
lower transport costs said nora lustig a former consultant to the 
mexican government and a visiting fellow at the brookings 
institution 
she said she expected to see more industry develop in northern 
mexico near the us border she saw textiles and electronics as 
two areas where mexico has much to offer investors 
ms lustig and ernest l preeg a former state department trade 
specialist who holds a chair in international business at the 
center for strategic and international studies said prospects of a 
freetrade pact would pay immediate psychological dividends even if 
a treaty takes time to iron out 
investment is likely to increase as business people are 
reassured by the prospect of steady sales in the huge us market 
for the mexican goods they said 
in addition to us and canadian investors companies in other 
industrial countries will want to start manufacturing in a place 
where costs are low and restrictions will be few on sales to the 
united states preeg said confidence stemming from freetrade 
prospects also could bring home some of the tens of billions of 
dollars wealthy mexicans have stashed abroad he said 
the two analysts saw broad advantages for both mexico and the 
united states from a freetrade agreement the two countries want 
to see more jobs created in mexico so more mexicans will stay at 
home instead of migrating legally or illegally to the united 
states 
ms lustig said a treaty would give us companies a chance to 
boost sales of machinery to equip the new factories in mexico and 
the possibility of making products such as auto parts more cheaply 
