<TEXT>
the government plans to link the pound to europes 
exchange rate mechanism in the fourth quarter of this year the 
financial times reported tuesday 
the newspaper said treasury officials have decided recently that 
britains underlying annual inflation rate will be low enough 
toward years end to allow the pound to enter the european monetary 
systems exchange rate mechanism 
the underlying inflation rate is now about 625 percent and the 
full rate including mortgage payments is 94 percent 
a spokesman for prime minister margaret thatchers office said 
the financial times report was pure speculation 
mrs thatcher said at a european community summit last june that 
britain would link the pound once british inflation is nearer the 
community average now about 5 percent and there is free movement 
of capital in the community 
the exchange rate mechanism links nine of the 12 currencies of 
the community to prevent wide swings in rates 
in a statement to parliament on thursday chancellor of the 
exchequer john major said the government will calculate its 
inflation in a way similar to methods used by other community 
nations 
his remarks were taken to mean that the treasury would strip out 
such things as the mortgage interest payments from the british 
index 
major also said significant progress has been made toward 
meeting mrs thatchers conditions but british inflation was still 
too high compared with the ec average 
the financial times said the specific timing of the pounds 
entry into the exchange rate mechanism will depend on sterling 
staying strong against other european currencies putting the pound 
into the system at a high level would help control inflation 
the newspaper said the government considers it wiser to join the 
mechanism on condition that the pound be allowed to move within a 6 
percent band rather than the 225 percent band to which most of 
the systems currencies are limited 
</TEXT>
