<TEXT>
federal law should be changed to allow 
consumers not private credit reporting bureaus to control the 
use of their credit records a house subcommittee was told today 
credit records are more than just account numbers they are a 
consumers reputation rep matthew rinaldo rnj told the 
house banking subcommittee on consumer affairs 
the panel is considering ways to update the 20yearold fair 
credit reporting act to keep up with major advances in computer 
technology that have made credit reporting a booming business 
rinaldo sponsor of one of three proposed bills said credit 
reports should be provided only for transactions initiated by 
consumers not for such things as directmail marketing mailing 
lists or preapproved lines of credit 
however jean noonan associate director of the federal trade 
commissions bureau of consumer protection said that although 
there is a danger that use of credit reports can be an invasion of 
privacy her office would rather regulate it than ban it 
subcommittee chairman richard lehman dcalif has proposed 
allowing credit reports to be used for solicitation if consumers 
are allowed to bar their own files from such use 
rep charles schumer dny is sponsoring a proposal similar 
to rinaldos to ban such use of consumer credit files 
rep john hiler rind ranking minority member of the 
subcommittee said the proposals went too far 
we also have to be concerned that we do not shut off the flow 
of credit to all but the most goldplated credit risks hiler 
said 
bonnie guiton director of the us office of consumer affairs 
opposed proposals to require credit reporting companies to provide 
customers a free annual copy of their credit record the consumers 
will end up paying the cost she said adding that credit companies 
instead should have to conduct random checks on their own work and 
publish the results 
the various proposals also include language to give consumers 
new power to correct errors in their credit reports and require 
that they be notified when their credit report is used to deny them 
a transaction 
on monday a louis harris amp associates poll reported that 71 
percent of those americans surveyed believe consumers have lost 
control over how businesses handle personal information about their 
customers 
consumers want the fair credit reporting act updated to guard 
against misuse of personal information said alan f westin the 
columbia university professor who conducted the survey 
but westin said consumers were willing to make a fair 
information bargain with the government and industry so they can 
still have access to conveniences such as directmail and credit 
cards 
consumers want it all he said they want both privacy and 
they want the benefits of a consumer society 
the survey was commissioned by equifax an atlantabased company 
that provides information and technology to businesses including 
employers insurers and credit companies 
it found that 79 percent of those questioned were either very 
concerned or somewhat concerned about threats to their personal 
privacy compared with 77 percent in a 1983 harris survey and 64 
percent in a 1978 poll 
in 1970 only 34 percent said they were concerned about privacy 
issues 
a large majority said privacy should be considered a fundamental 
right and 30 percent said they had decided against applying for a 
job credit or insurance because they didnt want to provide 
certain kinds of information about themselves the survey found 
but 78 percent said they would be upset if they couldnt get 
credit based on their record of paying bills 
the random telephone poll included 2254 interviews in january 
and february and 2253 interviews in april with about half of the 
first group of people being reinterviewed the margin of error was 
plus or minus 2 percentage points 
</TEXT>
