<TEXT>
the european community on tuesday submitted a 
proposal to liberalize trade in textiles and clothing by phasing 
out an existing agreement that regulates commerce in the 
politically sensitive sector 
the ec plan presented to members of the 96nation general 
agreement on tariffs and trade aims at bringing trade in textiles 
into conformity with gatts free trade principles 
the sector has for the past 30 years been governed by the 
multifiber arrangement which provides for quotas negotiated on a 
bilateral basis the current mfa is due to expire in july 1991 
world trade in textiles totalled 89 billion in 1988 while the 
clothing sector was worth some 88 billion according to figures 
from the genevabased gatt secretariat 
the ec plan proposes that most existing mfa quotas should be 
gradually enlarged by a given percentage before they are finally 
abolished according to trade officials 
however the ec also said it was prepared to negotiate a list of 
some products that could be brought into the gatt before the 
transition period begins 
the 12nation trading bloc did not set a timetable for 
liberalizing trade or specify the pace at which quotas should be 
increased during the transition period trade officials said 
one source who declined to be identified said some negotiators 
at the meeting criticized the proposals for being too imprecise 
the ec plan to start from the basis of the existing mfa 
contrasts with the us approach the united states wants to 
abandon the mfa when it expires next year and introduce a new 
10year global quota system critics of the american plan argue 
that washington is seeking to introduce new restrictions through 
this scheme in order to placate its powerful textile lobby which 
fears competition from third world exporters 
the 22nation international textiles and clothing bureau which 
represents major third world producers is due to present a 
proposal on wednesday to phase out restrictions on their exports 
within six years 
new rules on textiles are due to be resolved in december when 
the fouryear uruguay round of negotiations is scheduled to end 
</TEXT>
