<TEXT>
japans trade surplus declined slightly in may the 
12th month in the last 13 during which the surplus narrowed from a 
year earlier the finance ministry reported tuesday 
the may surplus of 313 billion compared with 376 billion in 
may 1989 exports fell 09 percent from a year earlier to 2152 
billion while imports grew by 24 percent to 1838 billion 
economists said a slowing in the rate of export declines 
indicated the yens recent weakness may cause a renewed buildup in 
the surplus they added that slower growth in the domestic economy 
may be depressing imports 
a cheaper yen makes japanese goods more competitive in price 
overseas 
after seeing these figures im confident that possibly as 
early as july we could see a widening in japans trade surplus 
said jesper koll an economist at sg warburg securities 
bank of tokyo economist toshio yamasaki said a weaker domestic 
economy will encourage companies to ship their products abroad 
lower oil prices also reduced the value of japans imports in 
may its crude oil imports increased 31 percent in volume but 
dropped 4 percent in value terms to 171 billion japanese 
importers paid an average of 1679 a barrel for crude oil in may 
down from 1802 a year earlier 
in trade with the united states japans surplus shrank to 244 
billion in may from 276 billion a year earlier 
japanese companies exported 682 billion worth of goods to the 
united states in may down 45 percent from a year earlier imports 
from the united states fell 02 percent to 438 billion 
japans surplus with the european community shrank to 12 
billion from 163 billion in may 1989 exports totaled 407 
billion up 71 percent against imports of 287 billion up 323 
percent 
