<TEXT>
itt corp said tuesday it will sell 7 percent of 
alcatel nv to its partner in the french telecommunications 
equipment manufacturing joint venture for 640 million 
the sale of the stake to frances compagnie generale 
delectricite will reduce itts ownership in alcatel to 30 percent 
which was the level itt sought to own in the 1986 negotiations on 
forming the joint venture 
but in order to assure completion of the deal which created the 
worlds biggest maker of telecommunications equipment itt in 1986 
agreed to take a 37 percent interest in alcatel 
itt will report an aftertax gain of about 139 million from the 
transaction which is expected to close on june 14 the gain will 
be included in itts secondquarter earnings the company said in a 
news release 
proceeds from the sale will be used to buy back additional 
shares of itt common stock under the companys stock repurchase 
program since the program started in 1987 itt has bought back 25 
million shares 
rand v araskog itts chairman and chief executive and also 
chairman of alcatels supervisory board said itts investment in 
alcatel has grown handsomely since the parisbased venture began 
our alcatel shares have more than doubled in value in three 
years and our board of directors is pleased not only with this 
outstanding appreciation of our investment but also with the 
positive working relationship developed between itt and cge he 
said 
the sale of 7 percent of alcatel will allow itt to realize a 
return from this increased value while retaining a substantial 
ownership position to take advantage of growth projected for 
alcatel in the future he said 
alcatels growth has been spurred by economic development within 
european community and eastern europe the creation of a single 
european marketplace is expected to enhance demand for equipment 
alcatel supplies 
itt said its assets in europe total 5 billion or 11 percent of 
its total assets 
the new yorkbased company is primarily involved in the 
telecommunications field it also has interests in the automotive 
defense technology electronics pulp and timber insurance hotels 
and finance areas 
</TEXT>
