<TEXT>
chrysler corp and french automaker renault on 
tuesday terminated a joint venture to build a small sportutility 
vehicle but chrysler said it planned to continue developing the 
project 
chrysler spokesman tom houston said the company which saw its 
first quarter profit drop by 80 percent decided the arcad project 
is no longer economically attractive 
chrysler intends to continue with the jj project and is 
reviewing various implementation alternatives houston said 
declining to disclose details his statement indicated the company 
may be considering developing the vehicle by itself or with another 
partner 
the collapse of the 500 million arcad joint venture could delay 
chryslers plans to expand in europe which is seen as a 
potentially huge market once internal trade barriers are lifted in 
1992 and former east bloc nations continue liberalizing their 
economies 
arcad was to begin producing the vehicle codenamed jj in 
the second half of 1992 at a valladolid spain plant leased from 
renaults spanish subsidiary 
the fourwheeldrive vehicles were to be marketed worldwide 
except in north america where arcad planned to build them at an 
existing chrysler facility 
during the past year chrysler has shown signs of growing in 
europe where it has had little presence in the past the company 
recently signed a deal to build minivans in austria 
last week general motors corp announced a joint venture with 
volga auto works of the soviet union gm executives said the 
project to provide fuel system components represented their 
entrance to a potentially huge marketplace 
it appears unlikely that production of the jj could begin in 
north america before late 1992 the original target date of the 
arcad agreement 
arcad had not said where north american production would be 
located but speculation surrounded chryslers jeep plant in 
toledo ohio 
on monday members of united auto workers union local 12 in 
toledo approved a new local labor agreement seen as key to bringing 
production of the jj and the jeep wrangler now made in canada 
to the aging factory 
the jj would be built in pieces by suppliers and shipped to 
an assembly plant said joseph phillippi an auto industry analyst 
for shearson lehman hutton in new york 
there is no stamping no machining no painting he said 
because of potential that the jj would have to be priced low to 
fight competition from the geo tracker suzuki sidekick and 
daihatsu rocky pervehicle profit would be relatively low 
phillippi said 
chrysler has been getting most of its profits from sales of its 
minivans and its jeep line which it acquired with the purchase of 
american motors corp in august 1987 
but recently chryslers profits have been falling its sales 
have been slipping and toplevel executives have been leaving 
the company earned 359 million last year down 658 percent 
from 1988 profits through the first five months of this year 
chrysler had sold 713883 cars and trucks down 128 percent from 
last year 
four top level executives including former vice chairman gerald 
greenwald recently have announced they were leaving chrysler or 
would do so by yeard end 
</TEXT>
