the department of transport said tuesday that 
talks continued between the united states and britain on allowing 
each others airlines to fly to more cities and the times of 
london said an agreement was near 
although a department spokesman said there was no indication of 
a resolution soon the times reported that the countries have 
nearly completed a deal under which american airlines northwest 
airlines and delta air lines would obtain rights to fly to 
manchester england from chicago boston and atlanta 
respectively all three already fly to manchester from other cities 
the airlines would be given the opportunity to vary those 
routes and they also would be allowed to fly on to paris and 
frankfurt if france and west germany agree the newspaper said 
without identifying its source 
in return virgin atlantic airways of great britain would be 
allowed to fly from londons gatwick airport to boston the 
newspaper said and british airways and other british airlines 
would be allowed to fly to major american cities from any regional 
airport in britain 
talks began more than a year ago on a new bilateral air services 
agreement to replace the bermuda ii deal which was reached in the 
mid1970s 
the times said british airways britains largest airline is 
strongly opposed to the agreement calling it a sellout of 
british aviation to the americans 
british airways says the right to fly from british regional 
airports to the united states was useless because there was little 
demand for such service the times said 
british airways flies to new york boston philadelphia 
pittsburgh chicago detroit washington dc atlanta houston 
dallas san diego los angeles san francisco seattle anchorage 
miami tampa and orlando fla 
virgin atlantic flies to new york miami and los angeles 
trans world airlines pan am american delta continental 
airlines us air and northwest fly to heathrow and gatwick 
airports in london to manchester and to glasgow scotland 
