<TEXT>
gasoline for july delivery soared more than 26 cents a gallon 
tuesday on the new york mercantile exchange erasing steep losses 
registered during the three previous trading sessions 
market analysts said the rally reflected a bevy of minor 
influences including jitters about the crippled oil supertanker 
mega borg off the texas coast 
on other commodity markets grain and soybean futures were 
mixed livestock futures fell while pork bellies advanced and 
precious metals were mixed 
wholesale gasoline futures settled 13 cents to 262 cents 
higher with the contract for delivery in july up 262 cents at 585 
cents a gallon 
west texas intermediate crude oil futures finished 3 cents to 69 
cents higher with july at 1751 a barrel wholesale heating oil 
ended 60 cent to 166 cents higher with july at 4829 cents a 
gallon 
analysts viewed the rally partly as a technical correction after 
a threeday decline in which the july gasoline contract fell a 
total of 248 cents 
buying by wholesalers and distributors in the cash gasoline 
market also contributed to the runup as did concerns about the 
burning supertanker in the gulf of mexico 
it tends to conjure up images of last years exxon valdez 
incident which sparked a huge rally in the gasoline market said 
james ritterbusch an energy analyst for painewebber inc 
an announcement from royal dutchshell group that it no longer 
would use its own ships to send most petroleum products to the 
united states supported prices the britishdutch oil giant has 
been concerned about liability costs associated with environmental 
damage from recent tanker spills 
the rally also reflected speculation that tuesdays weekly 
american petroleum institute stocks report would show a drawdown in 
us supplies of gasoline ritterbusch said 
but the report which was released after the close of trading 
instead showed a 511000barrel increase in gasoline supplies along 
with a 126millionbarrel rise in crude oil stocks and a 
479000barrel increase in distillate stocks 
the crude oil number also ran counter to market expectations 
while the rise in distillate stocks was smaller than most traders 
had anticipated 
